Blocking critics on Facebook: You don't have to go to public office if you're not ready to listen to voter criticism
The founder of our country understood what a critical press was.
The Americans loved George Washington, but it didn't stop them from criticizing him for everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Criticism, of course, annoyed him.
But he didn't shut his critics up.
Because as early as 1783, Washington said, "We can be taken away from our freedom of speech, and we deaf and dumb will be led as sheep to slaughter."
Now I'm going to go to the governor of Maryland, Larry Hogan, who should have tried to be more like Washington.
Hogan's subordinates blocked and erased the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinion on his official Facebook page.
And this week, the American Civil Liberties Union sued him for it.
The governor's subsidiaries called the lawsuit a nullity, and the comment on the Internet was written in the spirit of "so and what."
"It's just Facebook," a lot of people will say.
But it's important, too.
And that's especially important when it comes to a guy like Hogan.
He's an amazingly popular Republican governor in a democratic state.
He's ranked second in the country's 50 governors' approval rating.
Hogan is not a stubborn reactionary.
He demonstrated a firm hand in managing the state and his commitment to his principles.
He also uses Facebook as a primary mode of communication with his constituents and shows his bald head on his page after chemotherapy.
It is therefore unnecessary and ultimately harmful to block people who come to the Governor's page -- which is described as an official public forum and administered by the administration on the basis of taxpayers' money.
In an interview with the Washington Post, press secretary Amelia Ches defended the governor's actions, claiming that blocking comments was just their moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls, spammers, and haters who are angry on the Internet.
The Post spoke to some of the real people Hogan blocked.
And these are real people, not trolls, a teacher, a businessman, a pastor, who turn to their chosen leaders.
They all say that their comments were respectful, informative and not rude.
The pastor quoted the Bible, appealing that Hogan was a Catholic.
Lakshmi's lawyer, Sarma Ramana, from Bowie, Maryland, did not express hatred, but asked about hate crimes.
"I wrote a polite comment that I was disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news," she wrote in the section of the commentary to the article in the Post.
"I also don't like the idea that when a lot of people leave comments on the same subject, some people immediately say it's a so-called trick instead of admitting they're dealing with a large group of disgruntled citizens."
What governor's subordinates call "concentrated spam attack," others would probably call "active life-threatening position."
In the Facebook era, it is easy to edit your image simply by blocking critics or erasing negative comments.
It's a much less dusty job than it used to be when it had to send people, collect and burn newspapers with critical headlines, or arrest and silence protesters.
But that's exactly what's happening right now, only in numbers.
Hogen is not the first official to be criticized for refusing to listen to Facebook and other social media.
President Trump was sued by Twitter users, who were booked on his Twitter account.
One of the first, turning decisions on this topic was taken this week in Virginia.
According to the U.S. District Judge of Alexandria, James C. Kasheris, the president of the Laudon County Observatory violated the First Amendment by beating the voter in her Facebook account.
And in Kentucky, the Republican Governor Matt Bevin filed claims against the American Civil Liberties Alliance for his Facebook and Twitter behavior.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington’s era of affordable postal spending, it was about the same as the Internet today.
Between 1776 and 1800, the number of newspapers had quadrupled, and the authors of anonymous letters had severely undermined its credibility.
Even then, Washington was dealing with anonymous trolls.
People under the aliases of Juricola, Valerius, Belizarius and Porcius wrote letters to newspapers that mock Washington's decision.
According to historical documents collected by the George Washington Documents online project, his office was overwhelmed by petitions criticizing his position on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation.
But he didn't try to silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and speech lie at the very heart of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting it.
