Maybe these election staff members know something that we don't know -- for example, that if it weren't for them, Trump's tweets would be even more provocative.
We may never know about the tweets Trump didn't publish.
If his staff had saved him from trouble at least a few times, their efforts had not been in vain.
But no one has always managed to keep Trump from putting oil into the fire.
Part of the problem is that in the White House, divided into rival factions, people are constantly trying to advance their agenda by supplying Trump with material, reliable or not, which confirms their views.
Politico, which is exactly what this story is about, wrote in May about the tendency of the councillors to constantly give the president questionable information.
Here's an example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Trump's current and former staff say that Trump can react very sharply to negative press reports, especially those containing dangerous leaks of information, and will not rest until he finds out who was behind them.
This happened at the end of February, when someone gave the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com, the website of the Internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, in which Deputy Chief of Staff Cathy Welsh was accused of standing behind the leaks in the White House.
