The warning was given by Minnichi the day after the Italian authorities confiscated a vessel belonging to the German humanitarian organization Jugend Rette on suspicion that its crew was actually cooperating with traffickers and facilitating illegal immigration.
The humanitarian organization, which has worked for only a year, has declined to comment on the substance of the detailed charges brought against it by the Italian prosecutor Ambrojo Kartozio.
"For us, saving human life is and will remain the highest priority, so we are very sorry that we cannot continue to operate in the search and rescue zone," states the organization's statement on social media.
"We will only be able to assess all the charges now, after we have gathered all the information and can assess the situation."
The Italian authorities have been following the Juventa ship belonging to Jugend Retette since October.
His crew is suspected of having taken migrants on board by lifeboats, who were sent directly to them by traffickers, and allowing smugglers to leave with boats they could use again.
At least one such meeting was supposed to take place only 1.3 miles from the Libyan coast, as stated in the prosecution file, the content of which was published in the Italian media.
The crew is suspected of violating the orders of the Italian coastal authorities, which control rescue operations in the area, more on humanitarian grounds than on any other grounds.
The Code of Conduct presupposes, mainly, that the “Juventa” type of vessels will have on board an Italian police officer who will monitor their activities.
So far, only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue have agreed to comply with the Code: Save the Children, Maltese MOAS and Pro-Activa Open arms from Spain.
The latter stated on Thursday that it considered the new regulations unnecessary but acceptable, provided that they did not cause any “significant change or interference” with its rescue operations.
Among those who refused to sign, there is the Nobel Prize-winning MSF.
