Michelle Carter's conviction for reporting Conrad Roy's suicide.
A resident of Massachusetts was sentenced to two and a half years' imprisonment for using text messages and phone calls to induce her boyfriend Conrad Roy to commit suicide.
Michelle Carter, who is now 20 years old, will have to serve 15 months of her sentence behind bars and five more years of probation.
Carter was found guilty in June of the manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who committed suicide on 13 July 2014.
Roy's father said at the hearing on Thursday, "My family is devastated.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free until the appeal.
She was facing a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her lawyers said that both she and Roy were suffering from mental disorders.
Carter, dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, listened to the sentence standing, shook her hands and lowered her eyes.
"She killed Conrad Roy by her actions," the prosecutor told the court.
"She interrupted his life to improve hers.
She didn't accept responsibility," she said.
"She didn't show any remorse."
But Carter's lawyer said it was "a tragic case that she deeply regrets."
However, Judge Lawrence Monice said that in his opinion, her “age, maturity or even mental illness did not have a significant effect on her actions”.
The Prosecutor read out the statements of Roy Lynn Roy's mother, which says, "It's not a day since I didn't mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and the way I handle it - I try to support his sisters despite all the pain that will remain with us forever," he says.
Roy's sister, Camdin Roy, said that she was indissolubly motivated by the idea that she would never be able to attend his wedding or become an aunt of his children.
"To be with the man who has always been with me since I was born is the pain that will remain with me for the rest of my life," she said.
This case is likely to be a legal precedent, since there is no law in Massachusetts that would hold a person responsible for counseling a person to commit suicide.
In 2014, when Roy was found dead in the car with symptoms of carbon dioxide poisoning, Carter was 17 years old.
The case drew the attention of the entire country when it became known that he had been forced to commit suicide by Carter's message.
"You can hang yourself, jump off the roof, stab yourself with a knife, I don't know how many ways," she wrote in several messages sent two weeks before his death, when he was resting with his family.
A few minutes before she killed herself, she wrote, "You have to do this, Conrad," and "You just have to turn on the ignition, and you'll be free and happy."
Judge Monice said that Carter wanted attention by means of Roy's death, and he barred her from talking to the press to keep her from getting what she wanted.
The opinions of the lawyers on this matter were divided.
One of the few who defended Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted in 2007 for the murder of her British roommate in Italy and acquitted two years later.
A 30-year-old Knox published in the Los Angeles Times her dissenting opinion, saying, "Michel Carter deserves sympathy and help, not prison."
