Astronomers have found a hellish planet where even iron can melt.
After first studying the properties of the stratosphere of a giant exoplanet called WASP-121b, astrophysics were greatly surprised by its temperature, which is capable of evaporating iron and other metals.
Experts have noticed that water molecules are so warmed up by the light of the star that they emit infrared radiation.
The Hubble Telescope has captured the glow of water molecules on this gas giant: this high temperature makes the water in the planet's atmosphere glow infrared range.
WASP-121b refers to so-called hot Jupiters, gas giants, in size and mass comparable to the largest planet in the solar system, but tens of times closer to the parent star.
It only lasts a year on an exoplanet for 1.3 "earth" days, and its gas casing is heated to almost 2,500 degrees Celsius.
Climate change threatens the lavender in Provence.
It has become a symbol of Provence and South France, but there are now fears that it is threatened by climate change.
Lavanda has grown worse because of dry weather and insect diseases; this has caused constant headaches for scientists and farmers who are trying to find a solution.
Eric Shes, an expert from the Provence agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM, says: “Lavanda in Provence is indeed at risk because in recent years the plant has experienced the effects of climate change: in the spring and especially in the fall, the rains have been much lower.
It affects the lifespan of the lavender.
And there are little cicadas that jump over leaves of insects that carry microbacteria; in very dry weather, there are a lot of them."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender not only attracts vacationers; lavender oil is very much needed in perfume and cosmetology.
Eric Shes says, "Besides very long ears with a large number of large flowers, we have small, underdeveloped, weakened, or absent.
That's why we don't have any more parts that contain air oil."
The solutions currently under consideration include improving water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, as well as plant spraying with a protective mixture of clay and water and producing more drought-resistant varieties.
