Using a computer software analysis of DNA from Manning and using it to create three-dimensional portraits of individuals who could have had such a genome, Dewey Harborg created a deep, though difficult, manifesto about not only the plasticity of DNA data - different ways of interpreting them and the inherent determinization of these interpretations - but also the notion of identity.
Manning, who was born in Bradley Edward's name, but was a teenager who openly claimed to be a woman, was sentenced to 20 episodes in 2013, including six violations of the Spy Act, computer fraud and theft.
Her pictures in the prison were not available, so only one photograph of her was known: a grainy black and white selfie, where Manning, in the platinum shade of a wig, clearly felt uncomfortable, was driving a car; with that picture, she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey Harborg successfully completed his 2012 project, Visions of Strangers.
In it, an artist made portraits of unknown people using forensic evidence such as cigarettes and chewing gum, extracting DNA from this rubbish and creating images of how these people might look.
And then she got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They interviewed Chelsea Manning in prison and wanted some portrait to illustrate the article," explained Dewey-Hagborg at a preliminary screening of the new press exhibit.
At that time Chelsea was not allowed to visit and photograph, so they contacted her and asked if she wanted to get a portrait of her DNA.
In this unusual way, the artist and her imprisoned muse became friends by correspondence and exchanged several letters for two years.
They even wrote a comic book entitled "Depressed Images", illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, who painted a picture of how the president would mitigate Chelsea's punishment in the future and be able to visit the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama really decided to free Manning just a few days after the book came out was a pleasant surprise after seven hard years in a military prison in Kansas.
There's something deep and strong about the exhibition opening right now, when Donald Trump is declaring war to people who reveal classified information in government, and inventing new ways to incite Twitter animosity that he's supposed to soften.
When Dewey Harborg was asked about the timing of all of this, she said, "Nothing happens accidentally."
In an artist's statement written on the gallery wall, Manning's huge signature at the bottom (with a heart over "i" in her last name) calls for an end to "automatic separation based on sex, race, sexual orientation and culture".
On the opposite side is its mitochondrial DNA, a long caterpillar from pencil C, G, and A.
With 200 letters (or nucleotides as a scientifically elegant artist), Dewey Harborg was hoping to show how surprisingly similar we all are, at least by our biological structure.
"I hope to explain to people that our genome does not determine what we are, how open the genetic data for interpretation and how subjective it is," said Dewey Harborg; her 2007 video work "Fog Memory" is also shown here.
"The DNA can tell us a lot of different stories, and 30 of these stories are here."
The last part of the exhibit in the same room is the novel mentioned above in the comic books.
It shows Manning in King Kong style over the United States Correctional Cazarm building with a loudspeaker in his hand.
"If they kill your speech, they'll win," it says.
"So don't ever shut up."
"This is a direct quote from the letter she wrote to me," says an artist welcoming us from Philadelphia.
"I still have the creeps when I talk about it."
Manning hasn't seen the exhibition in person yet - as it was visually depicted in comic books - but when it comes, it will be greeted by masks in the center of the room, her own genome simulations, gathered like crowds of protesters.
It's also premeditated, just like everyone at the exhibition up to height (5"2, Manning's height), where the pencil painted genetic helogroups.
"I'd rather put them on the walls, but now I want them to look like a crowd of people," says Dewey Harborg about portraits.
