The disabled Anton Mamaev was fined
Mosgorsud commuted the sentence of the wheelchair invalid Anton Mamaev from four and a half years ' imprisonment to a fine of 200,000 roubles.
Previously, the convicted person was released from SIZO by a decision of the Timirazev court.
In doing so, Mosgorsoud confirmed that the accused was a criminal because he had arranged for the robbery and abduction of a motoraller from a former SWAT fighter.
Mosgorsud reduced his sentence to 200,000 roubles.
“Mamaev is the organizer of the robbery, which also constitutes a crime, and accordingly such a person must be prosecuted”, explained the “OJ” by the Spokesman Mosgorsud Uljan Solopov.
In the present case, the court took into account the state of health of Mamaev, the factual circumstances of the case, and the absence of aggravating circumstances.
In addition, the court applied article 64 of the Criminal Code, according to which a penalty may be imposed below the lower limit.
With regard to Assistant Mamaev Vasily Serostanov, the court did not establish the circumstances that would have led to a change in the category of gravity of the sentence and a change of sentence.
Anton Mamaev himself stated that he was dissatisfied with Mosgorsoud’s decision.
I'm disappointed in the court's decision.
The only legitimate solution would be an excuse, intending to go on fighting for justice.
His lawyer, Andrei Orlov, did not exclude appeals to the Mosgorsud Court of Cassation and the Supreme Court.
“We will use all leverage up to the European Court of Human Rights”, he said, “RIA News”.
Recall that 28-year-old Moscow Anton Mamaev, suffering from spinal muscle atrophy, became a criminal figure in the fall of last year.
The disabled man claims to have bought a scooter from a friend for 160,000 rubles to sell.
However, the owners of the motoraller, including a former SWAT fighter, claimed that the disabled and his assistant, Vasily Serostanov, had taken their property from them, threatening to use violence.
On 30 June, the Tymiraziev District Court of Moscow sentenced Vasily Serostanov to three years ' imprisonment and Anton Mamaev to four and a half years ' imprisonment in a general regime colony (art. 162, para. 2, of the Criminal Code).
The Public Chamber, the Attorney-General ' s Office, the Human Rights Commissioner of President Tatiana Moskalkov, joined the case after the disabled person had been placed in the SIZO.
As a result, Anton Mamaev was released from SIZO in mid-July by a decision of the same Timiraziev court.
The defence, in turn, appealed the decision of the first instance in Mosgorsuda.
