The White House bill cost the taxpayers thousands of dollars.
According to the records of the armed forces given to the magazine TIME, the White House's decision last month to bring a marine helicopter to the South Lawn for an event dedicated to American industrial production cost the taxpayers $24,000.
The white-green Sikorsky VH-3D, known as "Marine One", when the president was on board, became a central element of the 17 July White House event at which American construction programmes were shown.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pens, and White House senior officials have been looking at technological products from all 50 states.
A helicopter made in Connecticut was placed next to a boat from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a cargo truck from Mississippi.
According to the records of the First Marine Helicopter Squadron (HMX-1), the unit responsible for the helicopter management, the White House Military Authority ordered the presence of the helicopter in a private order, or “FRAGO”, only 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn on the occasion of a “unusual” event.
“I just wanted you to make sure that you knew because this is an unusually publicized event,” wrote Commander HMX-1 in an e-mail to his supervisor, the first Deputy Air Chief of the Marine Corps, on the eve of the event.
The letter indicated that the helicopter would arrive in the South Lawn at about 7 a.m. on 17 July to attend an event scheduled for 3 p.m. and remain there until the lawn was released between 6 p.m. and 9 p.m. on the same day.
The letter adds that if departure from the White House is delayed, a second crew will be required to return in accordance with the working hours limits.
The first crew accompanied the helicopter during the course of the event, while the guard of the unit remained close to the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records received by the magazine “TIME” whether a second crew was required as a result.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using State property for political purposes.
According to the records, HMX-1 clarified whether the activity was in conflict with this regulation.
“We asked, among other things, whether it was a violation of Hatch's law, and we were told that it was not,” wrote the commander.
“You seem to have nowhere to go,” the Deputy Chief replied.
The event “Making America” was declared an official event by the White House and was not subject to the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political notes.
During the event, the President made efforts to advance the reform of the health sector, which was at the time in the Senate, and praised attempts to regulate government regulations.
The use of aircraft known as Marine One and Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But it's unusual to ask for them only in the interest of photographic capacity.
Trump was already the subject of discussion in February, when the presidential plane drove in the background during its first election rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account was full of complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessor.
“The White House is thrilled with the "Make in America" show, which featured products from 50 states made by American workers from American material,” says the deputy secretary of the White House, Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews often fly around the Washington Agglomeration and on the South Lawn to train the President of the United States to transport to the White House to an inch.
When Trump was at the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 carried out 58 training landings at the White House.
According to one official, the flight carried out for the "Done in America" event was counted to the crew for the necessary training flights in a month.
The unit helicopters also overflew 11 additional hours on that day as part of “non-presidential support tasks”.
According to the White House, the taxpayers were not charged for any of the other exhibits presented at the event.
A representative of Sikorsky reported that the company had not participated in the South Lawn helicopter demonstration.
HMX-1 does not account for the presidential flight budget, and it is difficult to determine the exact amount spent on the event.
But according to Department of Defense hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's VH-3D rate of reimbursement is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records that air time in air was 30 minutes each way from its airstrip at the Quantico Marine Airbase in Virginia.
The White House claims that the real cost of using the helicopter is much lower than that rate.
“To calculate the cost for taxpayers on the basis of an estimated rate of reimbursement is quite wrong,” Walters says.
“These indicative rates include personnel, services and many other irreversible costs that are included in the annual allocation.”
According to a study conducted in 2015 by the RAND Corporation, the reimbursement rates do not include the cost of personnel, but indeed take into account the cost of fuel, maintenance and costs specified in the contract.
At the time, former White House spokesperson Sean Spicer spoke out to defend the use of the helicopter for the event.
“The idea is to show this week the things done in America,” Spicer said.
“And I know that Sikorsky and Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to national security, and that there are, I suppose, hundreds, if not thousands, of people whose jobs depend on it.
And I think, like most Americans, that we are all proud of this helicopter and other military equipment that so many Americans have worked tirelessly to build.
Therefore, of course, it is entirely appropriate to pay attention to this.”
It was not clear whether Trump interacted with the helicopter by inspecting the South Lawn during the event, but he was definitely sitting in a driver's seat in a fire truck.
Inside the White House, Trump approached Sikorsky's representatives, making a joke with the press about his own fleet of products.
"I know very well "Sikorsky," the president said. "I have three of them."
