Electricity is cheaper for both residents and producers of drilling.
The efforts of the Soviet and post-Soviet authorities of the Republic of Buryatia (East Siberia) to establish fair tariffs for electric energy users have been beginning to bear fruit for decades.
Since 1 September, the cost of electricity in low voltage for industrial recipients has decreased by 25 per cent.
The Federal Antimonopoly Service of the Russian Federation, in accordance with the Decision of the Government of the Russian Federation “On the amendment of the Regulation on the wholesale market for electricity and power and on the combined forecast balance of the production and supply of electricity (power) within the framework of the Russian Unified Energy System for the constituents of the Russian Federation” (No. 842), established indicative prices for electricity and power for industrial consumers of the Republic of Buryatia.
As a result, the cost of electric energy for drilling manufacturers is reduced by a quarter, which will greatly facilitate the lives of small and medium-sized enterprises and individual entrepreneurs.
For many decades, the leaders of the Republic have overstretched the thresholds of the Moscow cabinets in futile attempts to equalize the region in tariffs with the neighbouring Irkut region with the cascade of hydroelectric power plants in Angar, which comes from Baikala, for which Buryatia is the main catchment area.
And it was only this year that the changes began.
In March, electricity tariffs for the population of the Republic were reduced from 4.24 roubles/kWh to 3.93 roubles/kWh, or 7.3 per cent.
With the inclusion of Buritia by decision of the Federal Government on the list of wholesale market price zones for which the characteristics of wholesale and retail markets are determined, industrial consumers have emerged.
